<p>Is your A/B test taking too long to hit 95% statistical significance?</p=
>



<p>Understanding stat sig (as the term is fondly called) and how the metric=
 works can ease your pain.</p>



<p>Right now, you=E2=80=99re probably losing patience and wondering</p>



<p><em>Do I even need to hit 95? There=E2=80=99s a clear winner in front of=
 me, and time is running out. Can=E2=80=99t we just move on already?</em></=
p>



<p>But you don=E2=80=99t have to feel this way.</p>



<p>If you can relate to the =E2=80=9CI must hit 95% before I trust my resul=
t=E2=80=9D experience, you=E2=80=99re currently being held down by one or m=
ore misconceptions about stat sig.</p>



<p>For your A/B test to give you the real answers you=E2=80=99re looking fo=
r, you=E2=80=99re going to need to flex some stats muscles.</p>



<p>But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean you have to become a statistical genius, y=
ou just need to understand how these concepts apply to your focus: <strong>=
randomized controlled experiments for digital assets</strong>.</p>



<p>That=E2=80=99s what this article is all about=E2=80=94everything you nee=
d to know to understand the reality of statistical significance in A/B test=
ing, how to get the true story from your results (even when they don=E2=80=
=99t hit 95% stat sig), and ultimately, how to shake off the misconceptions=
 that want to rain on your A/B parade.</p>





<p>Let=E2=80=99s start by defining statistical significance.</p>


<div class=3D"py-3 px-6 mt-6 border border-rose-100 rounded-lg">
  <h2 class=3D"text-4xl bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-b from-rose-500 to-rose=
-700 !text-white/0" id=3D"what-is-statistical-significance">What Is Statist=
ical Significance?<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"An=
chor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog=
/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#what-is-statistical-significance" st=
yle=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h2>
  <div class=3D"pb-6">
    <p><b>Short answer:</b> Statistical significance tells you if you can t=
rust the observed results or not.</p>
<p><b>Long answer:</b> Statistical significance measures the certainty of a=
 result obtained from an experiment. The higher its value, the more you can=
 trust that the result is not due to randomness, and that it was caused by =
the changes you did in your experiment.</p>
  </div>
</div>


<p>When analyzing A/B testing results, a <strong>strong</strong> statistica=
l significance means the changes you=E2=80=99re testing are <strong>more li=
kely</strong> to have had an effect on the outcome observed.</p>



<p>On the other hand, a <strong>weak </strong>statistical significance mean=
s the changes you=E2=80=99re testing are<strong> less likely</strong> to ha=
ve had an effect on the outcome, and the change in outcome likely came by c=
hance or luck. More often than not, it is <strong>safe</strong> to assume s=
tatistical significance values below 95% as meaningless.</p>



<p>If in your test, B beat A and the result showed a <strong>weak</strong> =
stat sig, rerunning the test may show a different result.</p>



<p>Measuring statistical significance is a way for you to be as certain=E2=
=80=93or confident=E2=80=93about your outcomes as possible (more on this la=
ter).</p>



<p>This is important because you want to be sure that the changes you imple=
ment will continue to show effects in the same direction as observed during=
 the experiments after it is done.</p>



<p>Your stat sig can be set at any benchmark. Some people choose a statisti=
cal significance of 95%, while some go with 99%. Your choice of benchmark d=
epends on the context of your test and the amount of risk you=E2=80=99re wi=
lling to take with the certainty of your results.</p>



<div class=3D"center flex flex-column items-center u-my-48"><iframe loading=
=3D"lazy" src=3D"cid:frame-33B2604F9A6C5A315CE6200E8997D0DF@mhtml.blink" he=
ight=3D"900" width=3D"504" frameborder=3D"0" allowfullscreen=3D"" title=3D"=
Embedded post" class=3D"grid__12 grid__8--tb" data-rocket-lazyload=3D"fitvi=
dscompatible" data-lazy-src=3D"https://www.linkedin.com/embed/feed/update/u=
rn:li:ugcPost:6908082496018468865"></iframe></div>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s look at an example of a statistical significance metric in=
 action by first calculating the value.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"how-to-calculate-statistical-significa=
nce">How to Calculate Statistical Significance?<a class=3D"anchorjs-link au=
toscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D=
"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-how-t=
o-calculate-statistical-significance" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons=
; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>You can use <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statisti=
cal-significance/#statistical-significance-calculators-statisticians-use" c=
lass=3D"autoscrolling">simple calculator tools</a> to help you calculate th=
e ideal sample size to wait for in your experiment before making a decision=
, based on statistical significance.</p>



<p>But if you=E2=80=99d like a stronger grasp on the concept, let=E2=80=99s=
 nerd out and see how it=E2=80=99s done (in one scenario).</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/=
wp-content/uploads/2022/03/Math-is-Coming-Meme.jpg" data-a11y-dialog-show=
=3D"previewDialog"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"400" src=
