></figure></div>


<p>In summary, these are the steps:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Create your null and alternate hypothesis</li>



<li>Choose your type of test</li>



<li>Determine your alpha value</li>



<li>Determine the sample size</li>



<li>Calculate the required values (i.e. standard deviation, standard error,=
 etc.)</li>



<li>Use a t-table to find your statistical significance</li>
</ol>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s go=E2=80=A6</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-1-create-your-null-and-alternate-=
hypothesis"><a></a><strong>Step 1: Create your null and alternate hypothesi=
s</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" da=
ta-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-tes=
ting/statistical-significance/#h-step-1-create-your-null-and-alternate-hypo=
thesis" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a>=
</h4>



<p>For your first step in calculating statistical significance, take a skep=
tical stance and state that the change has no effect on the result. This is=
 your null hypothesis, H<sub>o</sub>.</p>



<p>Its contender, the alternate hypothesis, H<sub>a</sub>, assumes the chan=
ge influenced the result. You don=E2=80=99t need to believe either of these=
, they=E2=80=99re just necessary for an unbiased test.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-2-choose-your-test"><a></a><stron=
g>Step 2: Choose your test</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling"=
 aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www=
.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-step-2-choose-you=
r-test" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a>=
</h4>



<p>There are two types of tests: z-tests and t-tests. You use z-test when y=
ou know the standard deviation and t-test when it=E2=80=99s unknown.</p>



<p>Under each option, you have two kinds each:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>One-tailed z-test or two-tailed z-test, and</li>



<li>One-tailed t-test or two-tailed t-test</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>What=E2=80=99s the difference between one- and two-tailed tests?=
</strong> One-tailed tests explore the possibility of there being a relatio=
nship between the change and effect in one direction (positive or negative)=
.</p>



<p>While two-tailed tests explore that possibility in both directions (posi=
tive and negative).</p>



<p>To illustrate, you want to know if =E2=80=98B=E2=80=99 beats =E2=80=98A=
=E2=80=99 in a one-tailed test. In a two-tailed test, you also want to know=
 if =E2=80=98B=E2=80=99 performs <em>worse</em> than =E2=80=98A=E2=80=99.</=
p>



<p>You need two-tailed tests in A/B testing. Convert Experiences uses <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/decode-master-ab-testing-sta=
tistics/">two-tailed Z-tests</a>.</p>



<p>For this explanation of the manual stat sig calculation process, we=E2=
=80=99ll work with a two-tailed t-test. You=E2=80=99ll get a wide-enough vi=
ew of how it is calculated for continuous metrics like revenue.</p>



<p>Next=E2=80=A6</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-3-determine-your-alpha-value"><a>=
</a><strong>Step 3: Determine your alpha value</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs=
-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B"=
 href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/=
#h-step-3-determine-your-alpha-value" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons=
; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>Alpha, =C9=91, is the significance level. This is the threshold value be=
low which you=E2=80=99ll reject your first (null) hypothesis. This is usual=
ly 5%, or 0.05.</p>



<p>The confidence level is 1 =E2=80=93 =C9=91, in %. In this case, 0.95, wh=
ich is 95%.</p>



<p>Alpha can be as low as 0.01 where you absolutely need to be confident in=
 your results. In the pharmaceutical industry or in life-dependent engineer=
ing design, like parachutes, you=E2=80=99ll want to be as absolutely confid=
ent as possible.</p>



<p><strong>Note:</strong> For a two-tailed test, =C9=91 is divided by 2. Fo=
r example, 0.05/2 to give 0.025.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-4-determine-the-sample-size"><a><=
/a><strong>Step 4: Determine the sample size</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs-l=
ink autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" h=
ref=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h=
-step-4-determine-the-sample-size" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; p=
adding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>To determine the sample size, you need to perform a power analysis. A po=
wer analysis takes into account the effect size, sample size, significance =
level, and statistical power.</p>



<p>The statistical power, =CE=B2, shows us how likely we are to declare the=
 alternative hypothesis as true over the <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com=
/blog/a-b-testing/stats-visual-guide/#the-null-hypothesis">null hypothesis<=
/a>. This is usually set at 80% and is what tells you what sample size you =
need in order to achieve statistical significance.</p>



<p>The calculation for determining the ideal sample size is complex, so bet=
ter you use a <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/calculator/">sample size c=
alculator</a> for this step.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-5-calculate-the-required-values">=
<strong>Step 5: Calculate the required values</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs-=
link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" =
href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#=
h-step-5-calculate-the-required-values" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-ico=
ns; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>These values are:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Standard deviation =E2=80=94 Measures how spread out the data you colle=
cted during the test is from the average</li>



<li>Standard error =E2=80=94 Shows how accurate your sample distribution is=
</li>



<li>T-score =E2=80=94 The magnitude to which your data groups are different=
 from each other</li>



<li>Degrees of freedom =E2=80=94 The formula is: (Number of samples in Grou=
p A + Number of samples in Group B) =E2=80=93 2</li>
</ul>



<p>You=E2=80=99ll need these to read the t-table in the next step.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"step-6-use-a-t-table-to-find-your-stat=
istical-significance"><a></a><strong>Step 6: Use a t-table to find your sta=
tistical significance</strong><a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria=
-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.conv=
ert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-step-6-use-a-t-table-t=
o-find-your-statistical-significance" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons=
; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>The t-table will show you the p-value for your data given the degrees of=
 freedom and other values you=E2=80=99ve calculated in previous steps.</p>



<p>One way of determining statistical significance is whether or not your p=
-value is below the value for your alpha.</p>



<p>If your p-value falls below your alpha, 0.05, you can <strong>reject the=
 null hypothesis</strong> and say the change had an effect on the result yo=
u observed.</p>



<p>If your p-value falls above your alpha, your experiment does not achieve=
 statistical significance. So, you cannot say for sure that the change infl=
uenced the outcome.</p>



<p>In this case, you likely need more data from a larger sample size.</p>


<div class=3D"default-box mt-6 py-3 px-6 bg-blue-25 dropshadow-light-blue r=
ounded-lg">
  <div class=3D"[&amp;_p]:px-0 [&amp;_h2]:px-0 [&amp;_h3]:px-0 [&amp;_h2]:p=
t-0 [&amp;_h3]:pt-0 space-y-4">
    <p>TL;DR: Using a statistical significance calculator is much simpler t=
han manually doing the calculations. We dive deeper into these calculators =
<a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significanc=
e/#statistical-significance-calculators-statisticians-use" class=3D"autoscr=
olling">further down in this article</a>.</p>
  </div>
</div>


<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"what-is-the-significance-of-statistica=
l-significance-in-ab-testing">What Is the Significance of Statistical Signi=
ficance in A/B Testing?<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=
=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.co=
m/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-what-is-the-significance-of-=
statistical-significance-in-a-b-testing" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-ic=
ons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>In A/B testing, we want to be sure the outcome we=E2=80=99ve observed is=
 caused by the change we=E2=80=99re testing.</p>



<p>We don=E2=80=99t want to end up in a situation where we wrongly invest a=
nd publish a change live that we expect to consistently produce more conver=
sion just for that change to not deliver.</p>



<p><strong>We want certainty.</strong></p>



<p>If an outcome is sustained over time, we can have a certain level of con=
fidence that it isn=E2=80=99t due to pure chance.</p>



<p>And that=E2=80=99s what statistical significance tells us about our resu=
lt: If you wait long enough for your test to gather enough data to consiste=
ntly prove the null hypothesis is false, then you have statistical signific=
ance.</p>



<p>This =E2=80=9Cenough data=E2=80=9D is determined by the minimum detectab=
le lift (MDE) and calculated sample size for the test, which you can get fr=
om a <a href=3D"https://convert.com/calculator">calculator</a>. More on MDE=
 below.</p>



<p>In research, statistical significance is used to guarantee the reproduci=
bility of a finding. The degree of guarantee may be stringent, anywhere fro=
m 99% to 99.99%.</p>



<p>In other fields or contexts, the degree may be more relaxed at just 90%.=
</p>



<p>In conversion rate optimization, the convention is to use 95%. This is t=
he stat sig you=E2=80=99ll find in most <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/=
blog/a-b-testing/a-b-testing-tools-2022-beyond/">A/B testing tools</a>.</p>



<p>But is hitting 95% statistical significance always necessary when runnin=
g A/B tests? Some tests just won=E2=80=99t hit that degree for one reason o=
r the other.</p>



<p>In <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/experiments-stati=
stical-significance-speed/">an analysis of 28,304 experiments</a>, research=
 findings show that only 20% of experiments reach a 95% statistical signifi=
cance level.</p>



<p>Does that mean that the remaining tests are a waste? No, you can still e=
xtract insights from tests that don=E2=80=99t hit the significance benchmar=
k. But how?</p>



<p>Justin Christianson, Founder of Conversion Fanatics, shares suggestions =
in <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/95-percent-statistic=
al-significance/">the video below</a>, such as increasing your sample size =
by driving more traffic to the page and running your tests on the high leve=
rage pages on your site.</p>



