</div></figure>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"statistical-significance-doesnt-stand-=
alone-what-other-concepts-do-you-need-to-know">Statistical Significance Doe=
sn=E2=80=99t Stand Alone. What Other Concepts Do You Need to Know?<a class=
=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-statistical-significance-doesn-t-stand-alone-what-other-co=
ncepts-do-you-need-to-know" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-=
left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>Some words and phrases we=E2=80=99ve used up to this point may not have =
made sense to you. So, this is where we=E2=80=99re going to dive into the d=
efinitions of each of these <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-tes=
ting/decode-master-ab-testing-statistics/">statistics</a> terms related to =
statistical significance.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"null-hypothesis">Null Hypothesis<a cla=
ss=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-null-hypothesis" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; pa=
dding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>A null hypothesis is the version of your hypothesis that says that there=
 is no real change.</p>



<p>If you=E2=80=99ve observed any change in your data, such as an uplift, a=
nd the null hypothesis is found to be true, it would mean that the change w=
as just random variations in values and noise.</p>



<p>For example, if you test changing the CTA button color on your landing p=
age from blue (original) to green (challenger) and observe an 11% growth in=
 conversion, your null hypothesis will be that there is no real lift.</p>



<p>At the end of your experiment, there are 4 actions you can choose to hav=
e in relation to your null hypothesis:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Reject the null hypothesis</li>



<li>Fail to reject the null hypothesis</li>



<li>Falsely reject the null hypothesis</li>



<li>Falsely fail to reject the null hypothesis</li>
</ol>



<p>1 and 2 are the actions you want to take. Rejecting the null hypothesis =
means you learned from the test that the green button color did actually ha=
ve an influence on the boost in conversion rate. Failing to reject the null=
 hypothesis means you weren=E2=80=99t able to prove that the green button h=
ad an influence on the conversion rate boost.</p>



<p>3 and 4 are errors. You don=E2=80=99t want to =E2=80=9Cfalsely=E2=80=9D =
do anything in online experimentation.</p>



<p>One way to avoid making these errors is by choosing the appropriate p-va=
lue for the specific test scenario.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"p-value">P-Value<a class=3D"anchorjs-l=
ink autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" h=
ref=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h=
-p-value" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></=
a></h4>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s assume your null hypothesis (the skeptic that isn=E2=80=99=
t ready to believe the results you=E2=80=99ve observed) is true, the p-valu=
e represents the probability of observing an outcome that is as extreme or =
more extreme than what you observed.</p>



<p>Meaning if it is extremely small, that event has a very small probabilit=
y of having taken place, meaning this reality that we are considering with =
the null hypothesis, can be rejected, and the change is indeed real.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"power-of-a-test">Power of a Test<a cla=
ss=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-power-of-a-test" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; pa=
dding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>The power of a test is the probability that an effect will be detected w=
hen there is one. This value is usually set at 80%.</p>



<p>The higher the power, the more likely you are to avoid making a <a href=
=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/optimization/type-i-type-ii-errors-inevita=
ble-in-optimization-experiements/">Type II error</a> (a false negative, fai=
lure to detect a real change when there is one).</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"false-negative">False Negative<a class=
=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-false-negative" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; pad=
ding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>Remember the erroneous actions 3 and 4 you can take with a null hypothes=
is? False negatives are number 4. This is where you falsely fail to reject =
a null hypothesis.</p>



<p>There was a connection between the change you made and the impact you ob=
served, but because you did not accumulate enough power in your test, you a=
ttributed the impact to random chance.</p>



<p>Coming to this conclusion can be a result of using a statistical power t=
hat is too low. You should have continued with your experiment until you ha=
d enough power to detect small changes.</p>



<p>On the flip side, you have false positives.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"false-positive">False Positive<a class=
=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-false-positive" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; pad=
ding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>False positives are also known as <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blo=
g/optimization/type-i-type-ii-errors-inevitable-in-optimization-experiement=
s/">Type I errors</a>. Here you falsely reject a null hypothesis. You saw a=
 connection in change and impact where there was none.</p>



<p>Among other <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/ab-testi=
ng-mistakes/">A/B testing mistakes</a> like ending your test too early and =
peaking, using a statistical significance threshold that is too low contrib=
utes to causing this type of error.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"minimum-detectable-effect-mde-size">Mi=
nimum Detectable Effect (MDE) Size<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" =
aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.=
convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-minimum-detectable=
-effect-mde-size" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.37=
5em;"></a></h4>



<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/minimum-detectab=
le-effect-mde-ab-testing/">Minimum Detectable Effect</a> is the threshold v=
alue for implementing a change. The MDE says, =E2=80=9CIf the positive resu=
lt (uplift) is higher than I am, then the change is worth implementing.=E2=
=80=9D</p>



<p>A high MDE means your test is set up to detect only major uplifts. With =
a high MDE, you can reach stat sig while using smaller sample sizes. But ma=
ke note, observing large effects while running A/B tests is rare.</p>



<p>For smaller lifts, you need a low MDE and large sample sizes. And large =
sample sizes take significantly longer to reach depending on your traffic s=
ize. So, you need to find a compromise between <a href=3D"https://convert.e=
levio.help/en/articles/84057-1-3-calculate-your-experiment-duration">how mu=
ch time you are willing to spend on an experiment</a> and the lift that wou=
ld be worth it for you to observe.</p>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"confidence-interval">Confidence Interv=
al<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-ancho=
rjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/sta=
tistical-significance/#h-confidence-interval" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchor=
js-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h4>



<p>A confidence interval uses a margin of error to present you with an expe=
cted range of outcomes. When you see the results from an A/B test, you=E2=
=80=99ll see a line like the following:</p>



<p class=3D"has-text-align-center"><strong>Difference in conversion rate (A=
KA lift): +13% =C2=B1 1%</strong></p>



<p>This means that the conversion rate may be higher (+) or lower (-) than =
13% by 1%.</p>



<p>If you run your tests for longer and increase your sample size for stati=
stical significance, your margin will get smaller and smaller.</p>



<p>There is, however, a point where the margin becomes so narrow and stops =
shrinking. The margin can never be zero because we live in an uncertain wor=
ld.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"statistical-significance-made-easy">St=
atistical Significance Made Easy<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" ar=
ia-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.co=
nvert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-statistical-signific=
ance-made-easy" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375e=
m;"></a></h2>



<p>Statistical significance is a complex concept that is often misused in t=
he world of A/B testing.</p>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s a real-world picture for you.</p>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say I have a page that sells my eBook: <em>How to Teach Yo=
ur Cat to Speak German</em>. I=E2=80=99m selling the book to cat owners in =
San Francisco, CA, and have managed to drive over 10,000 visitors to my sal=
es page with a conversion rate of 1.6%.</p>



<p>That means 80 out of 5000 of my visitors buy my cat training book.</p>



<p>As the CRO-savvy marketer that I am, I design an A/B test to try and boo=
st my conversion rate. The challenger shows a different cover image of my e=
Book that I believe is more persuasive than my original.</p>



<p>My null hypothesis: The new eBook cover image will not have an observed =
effect on my conversion rate.</p>



<p>My alternate (test) hypothesis: I will see a conversion lift when I use =
the new eBook cover image.</p>



<p>I set the threshold for statistical significance at 95%.</p>



<p>Assuming I 100% depended on stat sig to decide, at what point can I stop=
 the test and trust my result?</p>



<p>Do I stop when I have 100 conversions on the variant (the page with the =
challenger cover image)?</p>


