igcaption></figure></div>


<p>Sadly, my koala friend, stat sig does <em>not </em>explain everything. T=
his is one of many misconceptions surrounding statistical significance.</p>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s tackle these misconceptions one by one.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"only-when-p-value-005-can-results-be-s=
tatistically-significant">Only When p-Value =3D 0.05 Can Results Be Statist=
ically Significant<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"An=
chor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog=
/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-only-when-p-value-0-05-can-results=
-be-statistically-significant" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; paddi=
ng-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>As we=E2=80=99ve stated earlier, setting your statistical significance t=
hreshold at 95% is a conventional practice, but not a universal one.</p>



<p>This threshold is one you can choose for yourself, given the details of =
your experiment, the specific campaign you=E2=80=99re running, how much ass=
urance you=E2=80=99d like to have around your results, and the risks you=E2=
=80=99re willing to take.</p>



<p>There are situations where 95% is not considered good enough. For instan=
ce, when working with aircrafts, you=E2=80=99ll hear statements such as, =
=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s very little margin for error,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9CThis has to be perfect=E2=80=9D.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/=
