n></figure></div>


<p>Chances are your marketing campaign doesn=E2=80=99t share quite the same=
 sentiment as an experiment on an aircraft. But you can go with 99% to mini=
mize the chances of making false positives. This will serve well if you did=
n=E2=80=99t calculate the required sample size before starting the experime=
nt.</p>



<p>It all depends on how much risk you=E2=80=99re willing to take with your=
 next steps once you see the results of your test.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"a-statistically-significant-result-mea=
ns-your-test-will-make-lots-of-money">A Statistically Significant Result Me=
ans Your Test Will Make Lots of Money<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrollin=
g" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://w=
ww.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-a-statistically=
-significant-result-means-your-test-will-make-lots-of-money" style=3D"font:=
 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>This is absolutely not the case.</p>



<p>A statistically significant result simply shows that there is enough evi=
dence that the original unmodified version of a web page and the modified v=
ersion of the same page result in different outcomes (i.e the Null Hypothes=
is can be rejected). That there is a real difference in conversion rates, t=
hat the change that was made has caused a real effect.</p>



<p>This observance does not guarantee that the observed uplift is:&nbsp; </=
p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Going to propagate outside the controlled experiment environment<br><br=
>This is why accounting for shifts in traffic behavior, like seasonal dips =
or buying tendencies, is important.</li>



<li>Worth the resources invested in building the test out<br><br>Make sure =
you take care when setting the value for your Minimum Detectable Effect, to=
 make sure the juice is worth the squeeze. The ROI of your test is not the =
same as the statistical significance of your test.</li>
</ol>



<p>Basically, it is just a decision-making tool! Should we implement this c=
hange or not to improve metric X?</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"statistical-significance-means-you-can=
-pause-your-ab-test-early">Statistical Significance Means You Can Pause You=
r A/B Test Early<a class=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anch=
or" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a=
-b-testing/statistical-significance/#h-statistical-significance-means-you-c=
an-pause-your-a-b-test-early" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; paddin=
g-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p><a href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/experiments-statisti=
cal-significance-speed/">When you decide to pause or stop your tests</a> de=
pends on your calculated sample size.</p>



<p>Some tools give you the possibility to have stopping rules, but as a rul=
e of thumb, if you want to prove an effect, stat sig is the bare minimum. Y=
et you also do not need to stop your test as soon as you reach statistical =
significance, as it=E2=80=99s important to wait for the calculated sample s=
ize to be reached in order to minimize the chance of making a small positiv=
e, or missing out on a real effect, false negative.</p>



<p>When thinking about the latter scenario, remember that the true value of=
 stat sig depends on a number of other numbers, which in turn depend on oth=
er inputs. In an A/B test, your stat sig depends on conversion rate, and co=
nversion rate depends on the total number of unique visitors.</p>



<p>If on Day 1, 5 out of 10 people who visited your variant page made a pur=
chase, that=E2=80=99s a conversion rate of 50%. And when you look at your c=
ontrol page, the conversion rate is still stuck at 10%.</p>



<p>Right out of the gate, you have a clear winner, right? Worth celebrating=
, right? No, hold on a second.</p>



<p>At this point, the rates are so far apart you can see a high stat sig. E=
ven if the stat sig is over 95%, don=E2=80=99t stop. The statistical signif=
icance varies and balances over time as more data is collected. There will =
be a point where the significance balances within a certain interval and se=
ttles around +95%.</p>



