<p>PS: Pausing tests should be based on sample size, i.e. how many people =
=E2=80=9Csee=E2=80=9D the test, because at the end of the day an A/B test i=
s trying to quantify and explain people=E2=80=99s general behavior.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"you-can-calculate-statistical-signific=
ance-every-day">You Can Calculate Statistical Significance Every Day<a clas=
s=3D"anchorjs-link autoscrolling" aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=
=3D"=EE=A7=8B" href=3D"https://www.convert.com/blog/a-b-testing/statistical=
-significance/#h-you-can-calculate-statistical-significance-every-day" styl=
e=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h3>



<p>This is a classic case of peaking, one of the <a href=3D"https://www.con=
vert.com/blog/a-b-testing/ab-testing-mistakes/">most common A/B testing mis=
takes</a>.</p>



<p>Calculating stat sig every day shows ignorance to the fact that that sta=
t sig fluctuates. What should be paramount in the decisions you=E2=80=99re =
making about your test is the sample size.</p>



<p>Have you observed enough people to have the insights you need to make a =
definitive decision from the data collected?</p>



<div class=3D"center flex flex-column items-center u-my-48"><iframe loading=
=3D"lazy" src=3D"cid:frame-986EFE20EC1807A4450B187B4FC6F05F@mhtml.blink" he=
ight=3D"550" width=3D"504" frameborder=3D"0" allowfullscreen=3D"" title=3D"=
